gement Accident Prevention Program

The chlorination plant at the Lost Hills Facility is subject to OSHA?s Process Safety Management (PSM) regulations for all equipment and operations associated with chlorine storage and the chlorine injection system.  PFI?s PSM program includes the following stringent activities to minimize the potential accidental release:

? Review of the design of all equipment and controls associated with the chlorine injection system to ensure they are properly designed and installed;
? Initial safety training and 3-year refresher training for appropriate personnel;
? Procedures to ensure that all contractors have received safety training;
? Periodic inspections of all equipment and controls, with stringent documentation of all inspections;
? Prompt corrective action for any non-conforming items identified by the regular inspectors;
? Pre-startup safety reviews conducted prior to system startup, if any equipment or operations are modified;
? Stringent investigation of any incidents that have a potential to have caused chlorine releases;
? Periodic evaluation of safety records of all outside contractors who work on the RMP/PSM-regulated systems;
? Development of an effective emergency response program;
? Implementation of an employee participation program to ensure that all appropriate staff are aware of the PSM program, and are actively consulted regarding safety issues; and
? Independent audits of the PSM and RMP programs every three years.

Methyl bromide is handled at the Facility is quantities that exceed the OSHA PSM threshold.  However, since the methyl bromide is stored in 175 lb cylinders, a release involving 2,500 lbs of methyl bromide is unlikely and; therefore, methyl bromide has not been included in the PSM portion of this RMP/PSM.

